MAfc2V_EVtyR9rMxxEAPLg
Is it possible to get tasty Vietnamese at a place where you don't have to turn a blind eye to the unwanted glimpses of the kitchen?  Yes, indeed.  While not a stunning polished restaurant by any stretch of the imagination, Khai Hoan is an impeccably clean little family place cooking simple good food in a strip mall on Apache Blvd.   The selections are tasty, plentiful and cheap with apps ranging from $3-$6 and Mains running from $6-$7.    I enjoyed the usual Vietnamese favorites of spring rolls and pho.  While the grilled pork on broken rice was nicely flavored, the meat was a touch on the dry side.    My favorite is the pickled papaya with charcoal grilled pork and meatball.  It's served with rice noodles, lettuce and fresh herbs.  The charred savory meat is nicely balanced by the sweet and sour papaya.  The rice noodles are great for absorbing the tasty broth.  But don't go here on a lazy Sunday...you'll be sorely disappointed since the place will be closed.  Don't forget to pick up some baklava from Haji-Baba (in the same center) for dessert.

